üßµ MSME DUES LOST IN INSOLVENCY ‚Äî Where is our Protection?

As an MSME providing essential facility & housekeeping management services, we delivered work honestly, paid our workers, followed every statutory rule ‚Äî PF, ESIC, wages, insurance.

But when a large corporate client went into insolvency, we waited over 3 years‚Ä¶ only to receive 4% of our rightful dues.

No negotiation. No explanation. No access to the process. Just a silent haircut.

‚úÖ Our claim was admitted
 üö´ We were not invited to any committee
 üö´ We couldn‚Äôt vote or object
 üö´ No rationale or valuation was shared
 ‚úÖ We got paid ‚Çπ4 for every ‚Çπ100 owed.

Meanwhile, big secured creditors dictated the plan. And MSMEs like us ‚Äî who hire some of the most vulnerable workers ‚Äî were pushed to the bottom of the payout list.

üîç Under current IBC rules:

- MSMEs are not in the Committee of Creditors
- We rank below banks, tax departments, even employees under Section 53(1) Distribution of Assets during liquidation.
- Once a resolution plan is approved, our dues are extinguished

üì£ It‚Äôs time for India to walk the talk on MSMEs:
We are called the ‚Äúbackbone of the economy‚Äù, but where is the protection?

Can‚Äôt the government guarantee MSME dues in such insolvency cases?

Shouldn‚Äôt essential service MSMEs be treated on par with ‚Äòworkmen‚Äô?

This isn‚Äôt just about one company. It‚Äôs about thousands of MSMEs who will be wiped out if the system doesn‚Äôt change.

While I have taken up the issue with the concerned Government Authorities and also Appealed with the NCLT Bench but this needs a serious introspection by the Law as well as Policymakers in India.

The Yam as a Symbol of Igbo Culture

Yam holds a central and symbolic place in Igbo culture, reflecting history, agriculture, spirituality, and social life. The root of its significance lies in the Igbo people's long-standing reliance on yam as a staple crop and a cultural emblem of abundance, strength, and communal effort.

Yam is more than food; it marks the cycle of the farming year. The harvest is a time of celebration, gratitude, and communal bonding. The New Yam Festival inaugurates the harvest season, featuring rituals, music, dance, and feasting. It signals readiness to share the bounty and reinforces social ties.

The cultivation of yams is associated with hard work, endurance, and prowess. A successful yam harvest is a visible measure of a family's or individual's strength.
  
In traditional Igbo society, young men demonstrate their capability and readiness for adulthood through their ability to plant, tend, and harvest yams.

Yams represent wealth and social status. The size and quality of a yam harvest can influence the esteem in which a family is held within the community. Sharing and hospitality are integral to Igbo yam culture. Excess harvests are distributed or used to settle disputes, welcome visitors, and honor guests.

Rituals during the yam festival often include offerings to ancestors and spiritual entities, acknowledging the earth‚Äôs generosity and seeking continued fertility.

Covered Call Explained in a easy way:

Covered Call is like renting out your house.
You already own the house (stock).
You rent it out (sell a call option) and earn rent (premium).
If the tenant wants to buy your house at a fixed price (strike price) later, you must sell it ‚Äî even if the market price is higher.

‚ö° AAAR Upholds ITC on Electrical Installations Outside Factory
[TS-839-AAAR(GUJ)-2025-GST]

Gujarat Appellate Authority for Advance Ruling (AAAR) upheld ITC eligibility on wires, cables, and electrical equipment installed outside factory premises for electricity transmission, rejecting the Department‚Äôs appeal.

‚öñÔ∏è AAAR Ruling Highlights:

‚Ä¢ITC Allowed: The installation qualifies as ‚Äúplant and machinery‚Äù, as it directly facilitates power supply to manufacturing operations.
‚Ä¢Not Immovable Property:
‚Ä¢The underground cables were not permanently affixed to the earth and could be removed for maintenance.
‚Ä¢Hence, they don‚Äôt fall within exclusions for immovable property.
‚Ä¢Circular Support: Relied on CBIC Circular No. 219/13/2024-GST, clarifying ITC availability on components (like ducts/manholes) forming part of telecom/utility infrastructure.

üß© Key Takeaway:

The ruling reinforces that functional nexus and business use are the true tests for ITC eligibility ‚Äî location alone is not determinative.

#GSTLaw #AAAR #InputTaxCredit #IndirectTax #PlantAndMachinery #GujaratAAAR #Section16 #GSTLitigation #TaxUpdate

üíº Gujarat HC Dismisses Revenue‚Äôs Plea to Cancel Bail ‚Äî ECL Deposit Held as Valid Compliance ‚öñÔ∏è

üîπ Key Case Facts:
‚Ä¢Condition: Respondent was required to deposit ‚Çπ90 lakhs within 7 days as part of bail terms.
‚Ä¢Revenue‚Äôs Argument: The deposit was made in the company‚Äôs ECL, not through Form GST DRC-03, and hence didn‚Äôt reach the Government exchequer.
‚Ä¢Assessee‚Äôs Rebuttal:
‚Ä¢‚Çπ90 lakhs was debited from his bank account and credited to the Government account.
‚Ä¢Section 49 of the CGST Act treats credit in ECL as payment to the Government.
‚Ä¢Filing DRC-03 would imply admission of liability, potentially affecting the right to appeal.

‚öñÔ∏è Court‚Äôs Findings:
‚Ä¢Referring to Section 49 and the Arya Cotton Industries judgment, the Court reiterated that once payment is credited to the Government account, liability stands discharged.
‚Ä¢Revenue‚Äôs apprehension that the amount could be re-utilised was found unfounded, as the accused undertook not to use or seek refund.
‚Ä¢The Court emphasised that bail cancellation requires supervening circumstances or violation of conditions, neither of which existed here.

Early Life #LalBahadurShastriJayanti

Born: 2 October 1904 in Mughalsarai, Uttar Pradesh (same date as Mahatma Gandhi‚Äôs birthday).

His father, a school teacher, died when Shastri was very young, and he grew up in humble conditions.

He dropped his caste-based surname "Srivastava" early in life as a stand against caste discrimination.

Education & Freedom Struggle
Inspired by Mahatma Gandhi and the independence movement at a young age.

Joined the non-cooperation movement in 1921, was imprisoned for participating in protests against the British.

Studied at Kashi Vidyapeeth, where he was given the title ‚ÄúShastri‚Äù (scholar).

 Political Career
After independence, he served in various ministries including Railways, Transport, and Communications.

Known for being honest, humble, and hardworking.

In 1964, after Jawaharlal Nehru‚Äôs death, he became the 2nd Prime Minister of India.

Contributions
Gave the famous slogan ‚ÄúJai Jawan Jai Kisan‚Äù (Hail the soldier, Hail the farmer), emphasizing food security and defense.

Promoted the Green Revolution in India to make the country self-sufficient in food grains.

Strengthened India‚Äôs defense forces after the 1962 war with China.

 Indo-Pak War (1965)

Led the country during the 1965 India-Pakistan war.

His calm leadership boosted national morale.

Ceasefire agreement was signed in Tashkent, USSR (now Uzbekistan).

Death
Died suddenly on 11 January 1966 in Tashkent, a day after signing the peace agreement with Pakistan‚Äôs Ayub Khan.

His death remains surrounded by mystery, with debates about whether it was natural or not.

Legacy
Remembered as a leader of simplicity, integrity, and determination.

The Shastri National Memorial in New Delhi preserves his memory.

His birthday (2nd October) is observed along with Gandhi Jayanti as a national holiday in India.
